{
  "texts": [
    "Similarly, Batiibwe (2019) and Bray and Tangney (2017) observed that digital tools are frequently integrated in mathematics classrooms in non-transformative ways, serving more as ancillary tools than integral elements of instruction.",
    "Bray and Tangney's (2017) research shows that when digital technology is used traditionally in mathematics classrooms, it often does not alter the nature of task assignments, nor does it replace the pedagogical role of the teacher.",
    "Rather, it is employed to streamline calculations, which while useful for convenience, induces only marginal changes in mathematics teaching and learning processes.",
    "The 21st century has witnessed considerable transformations in education worldwide, largely driven by the imperative to inculcate essential 21st-century skills, such as decision-making, problemsolving, innovative thinking, information literacy and technological proficiency (Jackson et al., 2012).",
    "Traditional educational approaches that no longer meet the needs of students have given way to educational reforms and shifts in pedagogical practices (Jackson et al., 2012)."
  ]
}